    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The relative minor of Eb major is C minor, and you absolutely *can* see this using the circle of fifths, though it's a bit counter-intuitive if you're only thinking about moving *up* fifths. The circle of fifths is better for finding the *dominant* (the V chord), but the relative minor is always found by going down a minor third from the major key. Since the circle moves by fifths, we can use the *sharps and flats* to confirm the key signature!\n\nEb major has three flats ($\\text{Bb}, \\text{Eb}, \\text{Ab}$). When you move down a minor third from Eb, you land on C. C major has zero sharps or flats, but C *minor* shares the exact same key signature as Eb major—wait, no it doesn't! C minor has no sharps or flats, so you've stumbled upon a common point of confusion, as many beginners assume that *any* relative minor shares the *exact* same flats/sharps, which is only true if the major key is not in the key of C Major itself. For Eb major, the relative minor is C minor, which has no flats,",
